<TEI.2 ID="ch026"><TEIHEADER><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><TITLE>Letter, 1838 Feb. 15, Washington to Colo[nel] Thomas L. McKenney / Jno. [i.e., John] Ross: a machine-readable transcription</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cherokee Nation. Principal Chief (1828-1866 : Ross)</AUTHOR><RESPSTMT><RESP>Creation of machine-readable version:</RESP><NAME>Lesli Wall Zimmerman</NAME><NAME>Debra Jean Roney</NAME></RESPSTMT></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><PUBLISHER>The University of Tennessee Libraries</PUBLISHER><PUBPLACE>Knoxville, TN</PUBPLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Hoskins Library - Special Collections</ADDRLINE><ADDRLINE>The University of Tennessee</ADDRLINE><ADDRLINE>Knoxville, TN 37996</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><DATE>2000</DATE><IDNO>ch026</IDNO><IDNO>OCLC: 44799057</IDNO><AVAILABILITY STATUS="FREE"><P>This work is the property of The Tennessee State Library and Archives, Nashville, TN.  It may be used freely by individuals for research, teaching, and personal use as long as this statement of availability is included in the text.</P></AVAILABILITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC><BIBL><TITLE>Letter, 1838 Feb. 15, Washington to Colo[nel] Thomas L. McKenney / Jno. [i.e., John] Ross</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cherokee Nation. Principal Chief (1828-1866 : Ross)</AUTHOR><DATE VALUE="1838-02-15">February 15,1838</DATE><EXTENT>3p</EXTENT><NOTE TYPE="summary">This is a copy of a letter from John Ross, Principal Chief of the Cherokee Nation, to Colonel Thomas L. McKenney, commissioner of Indian Affairs, dated February 15, 1838.  Ross expresses his gratitude for the kind sentiments offered by McKenney on the deteriorating state of affairs in the Cherokee Nation.  Ross refers to the Cherokees as powerless and indicates that the sympathy of the U.S. government is their only hope for relief.</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="repository">The Tennessee State Library and Archives, Nashville, TN</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="collection">State Library Cherokee Collection</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="box">1</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="folder">23</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="document">ch026</NOTE></BIBL></SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><ENCODINGDESC><PROJECTDESC><P>Prepared for The University of Tennessee Digital Library</P></PROJECTDESC><EDITORIALDECL><P>Quotation marks retained as data except inside q tags</P><P>Errors in transcription of the printed text controlled with Microsoft Word spell-checker; text has also been thoroughly proofread.</P><P>Corrections and normalization represented by editorial tags.</P><P>All unambiguous end-of-line hyphens removed. </P><P>Catchwords and directional notes such as "turn page over" have been omitted.</P></EDITORIALDECL><REFSDECL><P>ID attributes provided for only those pages, chapters, or illustrations toward which a reference or figure points</P></REFSDECL><CLASSDECL><TAXONOMY ID="LCSH"><BIBL><TITLE>Library of Congress Subject Headings</TITLE></BIBL></TAXONOMY></CLASSDECL></ENCODINGDESC><PROFILEDESC><TEXTCLASS><KEYWORDS SCHEME="LCSH"><LIST><ITEM>Letters</ITEM><ITEM>Cherokee Indians--Government relations</ITEM><ITEM>Trail of Tears, 1838</ITEM><ITEM>Cherokee Nation</ITEM><ITEM>Southern States</ITEM></LIST> </KEYWORDS></TEXTCLASS></PROFILEDESC></TEIHEADER><TEXT><BODY><DIV1 TYPE="letter"><PB N="[1]"><OPENER><DATELINE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE><NAME TYPE="place">Washington City</NAME></ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><DATE VALUE="1838-02-15">February 15th. 1838.</DATE></DATELINE><SALUTE>Dear Sir/</SALUTE></OPENER><P>I have been honored with your note of the 9th <ABBR EXPAN="instant" TYPE="suspension">inst-</ABBR> the pictures alluded to, may, if a suitable opportunity offers, be forwarded to me here, or, otherwise, retain them until I come to <NAME TYPE="place">Philadelphia</NAME>&mdash;  When that time will be, I cannot, by the by tell&mdash;.</P><P>I thank you for the <DEL TYPE="overstrike">kind</DEL> expression of your kind feelings for my suffering Nation- and I pray you, to accept my grateful <ORIG REG="acknowledgments">acknowledgements</ORIG>, for the <HI>sympathy,</HI> which you, in common with the virtuous portion of your Countrymen, so deeply feel, for the cause of an expiring people, in their last agony&mdash;  As to the wrongs and distresses inflicted upon your own people, and under <ADD PLACE="supralinear"><HI>which</HI></ADD> the <GAP REASON="document damaged"> they <DEL TYPE="overstrike">can</DEL> <ADD PLACE="supralinear">may</ADD> be <DEL TYPE="overstrike"><UNCLEAR></UNCLEAR></DEL> <ADD PLACE="supralinear">removed</ADD>- for, the people have <DEL TYPE="overstrike">in</DEL> the remedy in their own hands, and they will no doubt, sooner or later apply it efficaciously&mdash;  But, alas!  What is the situation of the <NAME TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME>?  Powerless- And unless, the Cries of humanity &amp; honor shall be raised so loud as to be heard, and bring to their rescue the strong arm of justice, they are ruined <ADD PLACE="supralinear">and annihilated</ADD>.&mdash;<PB N="[2]">Once despoiled of <DEL TYPE="overstrike">a</DEL> Country &amp; home, and <ORIG REG="stripped">striped</ORIG> of the attributes of freemen, cheated and robbed of all his Substance&mdash;  the <NAME TYPE="person">Cherokee</NAME>, thus left <ORIG REG="penniless">pennyless</ORIG> with his character traduced by the tongue of Slander and the finger of scorn pointed at him, will make his exit <DEL TYPE="overstrike">to the world of spirits</DEL>, unpitied and despised by the Authors of his oppression &amp; destruction!!  The heart of <ADD PLACE="supralinear">a virtuous</ADD> man, may feel the pangs of these <UNCLEAR>regulations</UNCLEAR>- but, the tongue cannot express, nor the pen <ORIG REG="describe">discribe</ORIG> them  &mdash; </P><CLOSER><SALUTE>May health and happiness attend you, is the sincere wish of, <ABBR EXPAN="Dear" TYPE="contraction">Dr.</ABBR> Sir, Your <DEL TYPE="overstrike">with</DEL>  friend &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="obedient Servant" TYPE="contraction">obt Svt.</ABBR></SALUTE> (signed) <SIGNED><NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="John">Jno.</ABBR> Ross</NAME></SIGNED></CLOSER></DIV1></BODY><BACK><DIV1 TYPE="letter"><PB N="[3]"><P>Copy of a letter to <NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="Colonel" TYPE="suspension">Colo.</ABBR> Thomas L. McKenney</NAME> <DATE VALUE="1838-02-15"><ABBR EXPAN="February" TYPE="contraction">Febry.</ABBR> 15th 1838</DATE></P></DIV1></BACK></TEXT></TEI.2>
